{
  "answer": "**Iqbal's \"Shikwa\" (from *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 20) does not explicitly mention the Muslim conquests of Spain (Al-Andalus) by name.**[^1]\n\nThe speaker does, however, recall broader Muslim military triumphs and presence across regions, including Europe—where the Umayyad conquest of the Iberian Peninsula (711 CE) established Islamic rule for centuries:\n\n> We called the prayer in Europe’s churches, burning with Your light,[^2]\n\nThis evokes the transformation of churches into mosques (e.g., in Córdoba and Toledo), part of those conquests, but Spain/Andalusia itself is not named here.[^3] Other glories listed include Khyber Pass, Caesar's city (likely alluding to Byzantine/Constantinople campaigns), Persia, and Africa.[^4]\n\n**Note:** Spain appears as \"Andalusia\" in Iqbal's nearby poem *Tarana-e-Milli* (Chapter 23), nostalgically: \"O Garden of Andalusia, do you recall the day, / When on your branches high our nest in safety lay?\"[^5] If that's the intended reference, it may stem from a mix-up between the poems.\n\n[^1]: Full chapter: *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 20 (*Shikwa*), [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 20 (*Shikwa*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-e1af7a).\n\n[^3]: Searches for \"Spain,\" \"conquest Spain,\" and variants yielded no hits in *Shikwa*; \"Andalusia\"/\"Andalus\" hits only *Tarana-e-Milli*.\n\n[^4]: E.g., *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 20 (*Shikwa*), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-ec4443) on Khyber/Caesar/Persia.\n\n[^5]: *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 23 (*Tarana-e-Milli*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-dea2e4).",
